9.2 Signal Object Structure
Each detected signal should be represented using a minimal structured schema. This standardization enables automated processing, systematic classification, and traceability throughout the extraction pipeline.
Signal object schema:
signal:
  id: &lt;unique-signal-identifier&gt;
  category: &lt;signal-category&gt;
  source:
    repo: &lt;repository-identifier&gt;
    file: &lt;file-path&gt;
    revision: &lt;commit-or-tag&gt;
  location:
    type: &lt;line-range | json-path | object-path&gt;
    value: &lt;location-reference&gt;
  excerpt: |
    &lt;artifact-fragment&gt;
  confidence_hint: &lt;optional-signal-weight&gt;
Field explanations:

id: Unique identifier for tracking the signal through the pipeline
category: Taxonomy classification (structure, dependency, entrypoint, etc.)
source: Repository and file where the signal originates
location: Precise position within the artifact for traceability
excerpt: Relevant fragment of the artifact for quick inspection
confidence_hint: Optional weight indicating signal strength

Why structured signals matter:
Structured signal representation enables:

Automated processing: Pipelines can programmatically classify and route signals
Traceability: Signals can be tracked from detection to final blueprint
Auditability: Reviewers can inspect the original artifacts behind each signal
Quality control: Signal classification can be validated and corrected
Machine processing: Signals can feed into machine learning or pattern matching

9.6 Entrypoint Signals
Entrypoints reveal where system execution begins. They often provide the strongest indicators of component roles and architectural boundaries.
What entrypoint signals indicate:

Component types: What kinds of components the system includes
Execution roles: How different parts of the system are used
Interface mechanisms: How the system is invoked or accessed
Startup behavior: How the system initializes and configures itself

Common entrypoint signals:
API server entrypoints:
# main.py
from fastapi import FastAPI
app = FastAPI()

@app.get("/")
def read_root():
    return {"hello": "world"}

if __name__ == "__main__":
    import uvicorn
    uvicorn.run(app, host="0.0.0.0", port=8000)
CLI entrypoints:
// cmd/root.go
package cmd

import "github.com/spf13/cobra"

var rootCmd = &cobra.Command{
    Use:   "myapp",
    Short: "My application does useful things",
    Run: func(cmd *cobra.Command, args []string) {
        // CLI execution logic
    },
}

func Execute() {
    if err := rootCmd.Execute(); err != nil {
        os.Exit(1)
    }
}
Worker entrypoints:
// worker.ts
import { Worker } from 'bullmq';

const worker = new Worker('my-queue', async (job) =&gt; {
    // Process background job
    console.log(`Processing job ${job.id}`);
});

worker.on('completed', (job) =&gt; {
    console.log(`Job ${job.id} completed`);
});
Scheduler entrypoints:
# scheduler.py
from apscheduler.schedulers.background import BackgroundScheduler

scheduler = BackgroundScheduler()

@scheduler.scheduled_job('cron', hour=0)
def cleanup_job():
    # Run cleanup task at midnight
    pass

scheduler.start()
