Why entrypoints are strong signals:
Entrypoints typically provide strong indicators of component roles because:

They explicitly define execution semantics
They often include framework-specific metadata
They are typically well-documented
They represent intentional architectural decisions

Entrypoint signals therefore serve as reliable anchors for component identification and interface extraction.

9.7 Configuration Signals
Configuration files frequently encode structural relationships within the system more clearly than application code. Configuration often exposes operational dependencies, integration endpoints, and system parameters.
What configuration signals indicate:

Service dependencies: What other services the system depends on
External integrations: How the system connects to external systems
Runtime parameters: What configuration values control behavior
Environment requirements: What environments and resources the system needs

Common configuration signals:
Service configuration:
# config/services.yaml
services:
  api:
    host: api.example.com
    port: 8080
    timeout: 30s
  database:
    host: db.example.com
    port: 5432
    database: myapp
  cache:
    host: redis.example.com
    port: 6379
Routing configuration:
# nginx.conf
upstream api_servers {
    server api1.example.com:8000;
    server api2.example.com:8000;
}

server {
    listen 80;
    location /api/ {
        proxy_pass http://api_servers;
    }
}
Environment configuration:
# .env
DATABASE_URL=postgresql://user:pass@db.example.com:5432/myapp
REDIS_URL=redis://redis.example.com:6379
API_KEY=secret-key-here
LOG_LEVEL=info
Integration configuration:
// config/integrations.json
{
  "integrations": {
    "stripe": {
      "api_key": "${STRIPE_KEY}",
      "webhook_secret": "${STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET}"
    },
    "slack": {
      "webhook_url": "${SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL}"
    }
  }
}
Configuration signal strength:
Configuration signals vary in strength:

Strong: Service dependencies, external integrations, routing rules
Moderate: Runtime parameters, environment variables, feature flags
Weak: Logging configuration, debug settings, development options

Configuration signals provide important clues about runtime architecture that may not be visible in source code.

signal:
  id: &lt;signal-id&gt;
  category: &lt;signal-category&gt;
  source: &lt;repository-file&gt;
  location: &lt;line-range | object-path&gt;
  excerpt: &lt;artifact-fragment&gt;
  confidence_hint: &lt;optional-signal-weight&gt;

28.2 Core Evidence Schema
The minimal evidence object representation is defined as follows:
evidence:
  id: &lt;evidence-id&gt;
  source:
    repo: &lt;repository-identifier&gt;
    file: &lt;file-path&gt;
    revision: &lt;commit-or-tag&gt;

  location:
    type: &lt;line-range | json-path | object-path&gt;
    value: &lt;location-reference&gt;

  excerpt: |
    &lt;artifact-fragment&gt;

  artifact_type: &lt;code | config | schema | deploy | doc | test&gt;

  signal_category: &lt;structure | dependency | entrypoint | config | deploy | docs | test | observability | security&gt;

  strength: &lt;strong | moderate | weak&gt;

  created_by:
    extractor: &lt;tool-or-pipeline-id&gt;
    version: &lt;extractor-version&gt;
    timestamp: &lt;iso8601&gt;
This schema ensures that evidence references remain stable even as repositories evolve.

confidence:
  state: &lt;observed | inferred | unknown&gt;
  score: &lt;optional numeric estimate&gt;
  evidence_refs:
    - &lt;evidence-id&gt;
    - &lt;evidence-id&gt;

mapping_rule:
  id: &lt;rule-id&gt;
  description: &lt;human-readable explanation&gt;

  input:
    signal_category: &lt;signal-type&gt;
    artifact_type: &lt;code | config | schema | deploy | doc | test&gt;
    pattern: &lt;artifact-pattern-or-condition&gt;

  evidence_requirements:
    min_evidence: &lt;integer&gt;
    acceptable_strength:
      - strong
      - moderate

  output:
    entity:
      type: &lt;Component | Interface | Data | Workflow | Capability | Constraint&gt;
      subtype: &lt;optional-specific-type&gt;

  relation_generation:
    create_relations:
      - relation: &lt;relation-type&gt;
        target: &lt;target-entity-type&gt;

  confidence_rule:
    observed_if:
      evidence_strength: strong
    inferred_if:
      evidence_strength: moderate

31.2 Metadata
The metadata section records the context in which the blueprint was generated.
metadata:
  repository: &lt;repo-id&gt;
  revision: &lt;commit-hash&gt;
  extraction_pipeline: &lt;pipeline-id&gt;
  extractor_version: &lt;version&gt;
  extraction_timestamp: &lt;iso8601&gt;
This information ensures that blueprint outputs remain traceable to the extraction environment and repository state.

31.3 Summary
The summary section provides a concise description of the extracted system.
summary:
  system_name: &lt;name&gt;
  detected_components: &lt;count&gt;
  detected_interfaces: &lt;count&gt;
  detected_data_entities: &lt;count&gt;
  detected_workflows: &lt;count&gt;
  extraction_maturity_level: &lt;EML-level&gt;
This section allows reviewers to quickly understand the scope of the reconstructed architecture.

31.4 Coverage
The coverage section reports how fully the blueprint kernel was populated.
coverage:
  goal: &lt;complete | partial | missing&gt;
  capabilities: &lt;complete | partial | missing&gt;
  components: &lt;complete | partial | missing&gt;
  interfaces: &lt;complete | partial | missing&gt;
  data: &lt;complete | partial | missing&gt;
  workflows: &lt;complete | partial | missing&gt;
Coverage highlights areas where the extraction pipeline may have failed to reconstruct parts of the architecture.

31.5 Confidence Summary
This section aggregates confidence classifications across the blueprint.
confidence_summary:
  observed_entities: &lt;count&gt;
  inferred_entities: &lt;count&gt;
  unknown_fields: &lt;count&gt;
The summary provides a quick assessment of how much of the blueprint is strongly supported by evidence versus inferred interpretation.
High proportions of inferred or unknown elements typically indicate the need for additional review.

31.9 Extraction Metrics
The extraction metrics section records quantitative indicators of extraction quality.
extraction_metrics:
  evidence_ratio: &lt;float&gt;
  entity_count: &lt;integer&gt;
  relation_count: &lt;integer&gt;
  signal_count: &lt;integer&gt;
  evidence_count: &lt;integer&gt;
These metrics allow extraction pipelines to track progress and performance across large blueprint datasets.
